'From Squeak 2.4c of May 10, 1999 on 10 June 1999 at 2:24:33 pm'!!Morph commentStamp: 'tk 6/10/1999 14:21' prior: 0!A morph (from the Greek "shape" or "form") is an interactive graphical object.All morphs owned by a morph are held in submorphs.  All coordinates are global screen coordinates.  (Except those that are flexed, contained inside a FlexMorph.)All show on the screen unless they are 'hidden'.  Hidden morphs have the property #hidden set to true.!!HandMorph commentStamp: 'tk 6/10/1999 14:23' prior: 0!The cursor may be thought of as the HandMorph.  The hand's submorphs hold anything being carried by dragging.  There is some minimal support for multiple hands in the same world.!!MorphicEvent commentStamp: 'tk 6/10/1999 14:16' prior: 0!My instances describe input device events (stimuli) such as keystrokes and mouse clicks or movements.type -- a Symbol identifying the type of event (#mouse, #keyboard, #unknown, etc.)cursorPoint -- the coordinates of the pointerbuttons -- field of bits identifying the state of the mouse buttons keyValue -- ASCII value of the key pressedsourceHand -- the HandMorph that provoked the eventMorphicEvents are created when a HandMorph receives the message processEvents(see HandMorph processEvents). When a WorldMorph cycles, it sends each of its handsthe processEvents message. In that way the stimuli of the input devices get instantiatedas MorphicEvent (see PasteUpMorph doOneCycleNow and PasteUpMorph doOneCycleInBackground)--Spanish--Mis instancias describen eventos (est’mulos) provocados por dispositivos de entrada comopulsaciones de teclas o clics y movimientos del mouse.type -- un Symbol que identifica el tipo de evento (#mouse, #keyboard, #unknown, etc.)cursorPoint -- coordenadas del puntero del mousebuttons -- un campo de bits que identifican el estado de los botones del mousekeyValue -- ASCII de la tecla apretadasourceHand -- HandMorph del cual proviene el eventoLos MorphicEvents se crean cuando un HandMorph recibe el mensaje processEvents(vea HandMorph processEvents). Cuando un WorldMorph realiza un ciclo, le env’a acada uno de sus hands el mensaje processEvents. De esa forma los est’mulos de losdispositivos de entrada se convierten en instancias de MorphicEvent(vea PasteUpMorph doOneCycleNow y PasteUpMorph doOneCycleInBackground)--LC 8 June 1999!]style[(103 4 79 11 35 7 62 8 35 10 8 9 59 9 41 23 166 26 5 35 5 7 148 4 83 11 38 7 72 8 31 10 80 9 38 23 13 10 185 26 3 35 21)f1,f2i,f1,if2,f1,if2,f1,f2i,f1,if2,f1,f1LHandMorph Comment;,f1,f1LHandMorph Comment;,f1,f1LHandMorph processEvents;,f1,f1LPasteUpMorph doOneCycleNow;,f1,f1LPasteUpMorph doOneCycleInBackground;,f1,f2,f1,if2,f1,if2,f1,if2,f1,if2,f1,if2,f1,f1LHandMorph Comment;,f1,f1LHandMorph processEvents;,f1,f1LWorldMorph Comment;,f1,f1LPasteUpMorph doOneCycleNow;,f1,f1LPasteUpMorph doOneCycleInBackground;,f1!